				\begin{document}$$i_{{\rm transmembrane}} = N_{{\rm Ch},{\rm O}1} \times i_{{\rm O1}} + N_{{\rm Ch},{\rm O}2} \times i_{{\rm O2}},$$\end{document}itransmembrane=NCh,O1×iO1+NCh,O2×iO2,where itransmembrane is the transmembrane current, NCh,O1, and NCh,O2 are the number of channelrhodopsins in the O1 and O2 states, respectively, and iO1,and iO2 are the currents transversing each opsin's channel in the O1 and O2 states, respectively.

Assuming conductance of O2 is roughly one-fifth of the conductance of O1[19], we can rearrange the transmembrane current as the following.2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
