				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$P_i\left( {{\rm AP}} \right) = f\left( {N_{{\rm Ch},i},i_{{\rm Ch}},\phi _i} \right) \propto i_{{\rm transmembrane}},$$\end{document}PiAP=fNCh,i,iCh,ϕi∝itransmembrane,where NCh,i is the number of opsins in axon i, iCh is the current through the opsin channel and ϕi is the fluence rate at the axonal surface.

We define the function g(i) as the contribution of cumulative transmembrane current on the intracellular voltage, and the corresponding intracellular voltage’s effect on the likelihood of reaching a depolarization event. Variables influencing the likelihood of axonal depolarization have been analytically evaluated in previous optogenetic double-cable models20. We then express the compound muscle action potential (CMAP) as follows:4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\rm CMAP} = \mathop {\sum }\limits_i^{N_{{\rm ax}}} {\rm MU}_i \times g(i_{{\rm transmembrane}})_i,$$\end{document}CMAP=∑iNaxMUi×g(itransmembrane)i,where MUi refers to the voltage generated by each motor-unit and Nax refers to the total number of optogenetically active axons in a given nerve.
